The easy approach to this would be:

``` java
public static AnnotatedTypeName annotate(TypeName typeName) {
  return new AnnotatedTypeName(typeName);
}
```

We should investigate switching `TypeName` to an `abstract class` though.

What do you prefer?
- Add a `public final List<AnnotationSpec> annotations` to `TypeName`, evolve the builder, static getter and emit code of all *`Name` classes and remove annotations lists from `FieldSpec`, `ParameterSpec`, etc or...
- ...introduce an extra class named `AnnotatedTypeName` that extends `TypeName` and collects the annotations? Like:

``` java
public final class AnnotatedTypeName extends TypeName {

  public static AnnotatedTypeName get(TypeName type, List<AnnotationSpec> annotations) {
    return new AnnotatedTypeName(type, annotations);
  }

  public static AnnotatedTypeName get(TypeMirror mirror) {
    TypeMirror annotatedMirror = mirror;
    if (mirror.getKind() == TypeKind.ARRAY) {
      annotatedMirror = ((ArrayType) mirror).getComponentType();
    }
    return get(mirror, annotatedMirror.getAnnotationMirrors());
  }

  public static AnnotatedTypeName get(TypeMirror mirror, List<? extends AnnotationMirror> mirrors) {
    TypeName type = TypeName.get(mirror);
    List<AnnotationSpec> annotations = new ArrayList<>();
    for (AnnotationMirror annotation : mirrors) {
      annotations.add(AnnotationSpec.get(annotation));
    }
    return new AnnotatedTypeName(type, annotations);
  }

  public final TypeName type;
  public final List<AnnotationSpec> annotations;

  private AnnotatedTypeName(TypeName type, List<AnnotationSpec> annotations) {
    this.type = type;
    this.annotations = Util.immutableList(annotations);
  }

  @Override
  CodeWriter emit(CodeWriter out) throws IOException {
    if (!annotations.isEmpty()) {
      for (AnnotationSpec annotation : annotations) {
        annotation.emit(out, true);
        out.emit(" ");
      }
    }
    return type.emit(out);
  }
}
```

